            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="2"
                xml:id="pb-2"
                facs="#i2"/>
            <lb/>
Lecture 1.<lb/>
Introduction &amp; History<lb/>
of the<lb/>
Chemistry of Agriculture<lb/>
            <milestone xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                       unit="section"
                       rend="line"/>
            <lb/>
H. Davy<lb/>
Here what has been<lb/>
done towards the<lb/>
end<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="3"
                xml:id="pb-3"
                facs="#i3"/>
            <lb/>
1<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Lecture</hi> 1.<lb/>
At this period, &amp; before such an Assembly it will be<lb/>
wholly unnecessary it would be indecorous even to offer<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">arguments</hi> in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">favour</hi> of the cultivation of any branch of<lb/>
Knowledge that can tend to improve Agriculture.<lb/>
- The connection of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Chemistry</hi> with this most important<lb/>
of the Arts has long been felt &amp; acknowledged by all<lb/>
enlightened Cultivators - Chemistry is justly regarded<lb/>
as laying the foundation; for the most refined scien=<lb/>
=tific principles belonging to the subject; &amp; is in a<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">high degree</hi> capable of useful applications to the<lb/>
practical Methods of the Farmer. -<lb/>
- Chemical Science has for its end the explanation<lb/>
of the intimate properties &amp; constitution of bodies &amp;<lb/>
their effects upon each other: &amp; the means that it<lb/>
employs are experiments in which the different substances<lb/>
are made to exhibit their mutual agencies &amp; the changes<lb/>
that they undergo. -<lb/>
- The knowledge of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">process of Vegetation</hi> is of<lb/>
great importance in Agriculture; But this knowledge<lb/>
cannot be obtained unless the nature of the food of<lb/>
Plants be discovered, the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">influence of Soils</hi> upon their<lb/>
Roots; the effects of Air &amp; Light, &amp; dews upon their leaves<lb/>
be ascertained; &amp; the constitution of the sap in its different<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
states known; &amp; these are immediate objects of Chemical<lb/>
Science &amp; can be developed only by methods of Analysis.<lb/>
- <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">In the operations of Husbandry</hi>, there are<lb/>
many immediate benefits to be derived from an<lb/>
acquaintance with the experimental processes for<lb/>
ascertaining the composition of Bodies. - Thus,<lb/>
they offer easy methods of discovering, what is<lb/>
most <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">likely to be the effects</hi> of a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">new manure,</hi>
            <lb/>
upon what Soils it will be most efficacious;<lb/>
&amp; how far its power may be counteracted or increased<lb/>
by other substances They enable us to ascertain<lb/>
the relative nutritive powers of different plants;<lb/>
&amp; to detect the causes of the fertility &amp; of the bar=<lb/>
=renness <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of Soils</hi>. -<lb/>
- Instances perhaps are always more inter=<lb/>
=esting than general propositions. it would be<lb/>
easy to bring forward <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">very numerous ones</hi> of such<lb/>
applications of the Science; but I shall at present<lb/>
content myself with stating a very few. -<lb/>
- Any Gentleman who happened to find a<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag1"
                ref="#chemical_090"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag1">
          Limestone
          
        </term>
            </rs> Quarry upon his estate, which burnt<lb/>
into strong <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag2"
                ref="#chemical_010"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag2">
          Lime
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">made</hi> good mortar, might<lb/>
if unacquainted with chemical principles at<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
3<lb/>
once conclude; that it would likewise make an excellent<lb/>
Manure &amp; in consequence might apply it on a great<lb/>
extent to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">his Land</hi>; &amp; might be exceedingly<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">disappointed</hi> in finding that it injured <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Soil</hi>
            <lb/>
&amp; destroyed Vegetation for many years; which<lb/>
would certainly take place if it happened to<lb/>
be the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag3" ref="#chemical_096" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag3">
          Magnesian Limestone
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>; which though<lb/>
it has all the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">common</hi> indications of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag4"
                ref="#chemical_090"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag4">
                  <hi rend="underline">limestone</hi>
               </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
proper for <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">manure</hi>, is distinguished from it in<lb/>
a moment by a single <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">chemical experiment</hi>.<lb/>
The Magnesian <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#chemical_090"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag5">
                  <hi rend="underline">limestone</hi>
               </term>
            </rs> when thrown into <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#chemical_143"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag6">
          Aqua=<lb/>fortis
          
        </term>
            </rs> or even into strong Vinegar dissolves very<lb/>
slowly indeed whilst the common dissolves<lb/>
with <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">rapidity</hi> &amp; makes an effervescence<lb/>
twenty times <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">as great</hi>. -<lb/>
- Again, A person who happened<lb/>
to have abundance of peat Land &amp; who was<lb/>
acquainted with the use of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#place_028"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag7" type="place">
          Berkshire
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">peatash</hi> as a manure, &amp; with the profits<lb/>
of the proprietors of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag8"
                ref="#place_028"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag8" type="place">
          Berkshire
        </name>
            </rs>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">peat district</hi>
            <lb/>
might immediately suppose (if he had not<lb/>
studied the nature of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Substance</hi>) that<lb/>
his peat would produce similar <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">effects;</hi>
            <lb/>
&amp; might begin to burn it &amp; to apply it <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to his Land.</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
where it would perhaps produce no advantages; for<lb/>
the ashes of peats differ exceedingly in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">their nature</hi>
            <lb/>
&amp; a great number contain substances of no efficacy<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">as manure</hi>: but the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">ashes</hi> of useful applica= =<lb/>
=tion are easily known by a chemical process for<lb/>
they are <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">soluble</hi> nearly altogether in weak aqua=<lb/>
=fortis or in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag9"
                ref="#chemical_016"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag9">
                  <hi rend="underline">muriatic acid</hi>
               </term>
            </rs>; whereas the peat ashes<lb/>
that are defective in power are nearly insoluble. -<lb/>
- Once more - The efficacy of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag10"
                ref="#chemical_112"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag10">
          Marle
          
        </term>
            </rs> upon<lb/>
certain lands is well known; but there are some<lb/>
soils that it is not <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">capable of improving</hi>; To know<lb/>
whether a soil would be improved by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag11"
                ref="#chemical_112"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag11">
          Marle
          
        </term>
            </rs> in<lb/>
the common practice of Husbandry would require<lb/>
a laborious &amp; an expensive experiment; but the<lb/>
chemical means of ascertaining the fact are very<lb/>
simple. - If the soil does not effervesce when<lb/>
vinegar is poured upon it We may be certain<lb/>
that <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag12"
                ref="#chemical_112"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag12">
          Marle
          
        </term>
            </rs> will be useful; but there is<lb/>
every reason to believe that it would have no<lb/>
effect if there was a copious effervescence<lb/>
&amp; if as much as two thirds or even a half of<lb/>
the soil becomes dissolved in the Acid. -<lb/>
These circumstances are I trust sufficiently<lb/>
strong to shew, the intimate &amp; useful <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">connection</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
5<lb/>
existing between <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Chemistry</hi> &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Agriculture</hi>. And<lb/>
it is fortunate for the extension of useful discovery,<lb/>
that this <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">connection</hi> is founded upon very simple<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">principles</hi> which may be <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">easily acquired</hi> &amp; which<lb/>
are almost independent of the more abstruse &amp;<lb/>
more complicated parts of the Science.<lb/>
- The objects of the Chemistry of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Agriculture</hi>
            <lb/>
are very simple &amp; distinct &amp; they may be easily<lb/>
classed &amp; arranged. -<lb/>
- In the Natural order of enquiry the first<lb/>
subject that presents itself is the Knowledge<lb/>
of the Nature &amp; composition of Soils, - of the<lb/>
methods by which they may be distinguished<lb/>
&amp; of the conditions essential to fertility -<lb/>
The discussion of the constitution of plants &amp;<lb/>
of the natural Agents to which they are subjected<lb/>
properly follows - And on the comparison of<lb/>
the constituent principles of vegetable matter;<lb/>
with the constituent principles of Soils of water<lb/>
&amp; of Air, the general theory of the growth of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">plants</hi> is necessarily <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">founded,</hi> for all the organic<lb/>
matter that they contain must be derived either<lb/>
from the Land in which they grow or from the Atmos=<lb/>
=phere by which they are surrounded. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
- The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">effects of Manures</hi> whether they are<lb/>
such as supply immediate Nourishment to the<lb/>
vegetable organs or whether they are such as<lb/>
merely increase the activity of their functions<lb/>
merit in the highest degree, a full examination;<lb/>
&amp; from the Knowledge of those effects in their<lb/>
relations to different soils the general chemical<lb/>
Theory of the improvement of Land, the last<lb/>
&amp; most important part of the investigation is<lb/>
naturally derived. -<lb/>
- I shall endeavour in this Course of Lectures<lb/>
to pursue these objects in the order in which<lb/>
they have been enumerated, &amp; to bring<lb/>
forward all the new &amp; useful information<lb/>
that I have been able to collect with regard<lb/>
to them - I shall particularly attend to<lb/>
the experimental part of the subject &amp; to<lb/>
those operations which offer immediate practical<lb/>
applications; - &amp; I shall take the liberty<lb/>
of prefacing the investigation by <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">devoting</unclear>
            <lb/>
the remainder of this lecture to a sketch of the<lb/>
History &amp; progress of the Science; which will<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
7<lb/>
enable me to point out my authorities; to pass over<lb/>
the course of reading connected with the subject,<lb/>
&amp; to reason from what has been discovered, con=<lb/>
=cerning what still remains to be <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">discovered. -</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">effected. -</add>
            <lb/>
- To begin on this subject, "The History<lb/>
of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Chemistry</hi> of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Agriculture</hi> embraces but a<lb/>
short period of time - Chemistry as a Science<lb/>
was wholly unknown to the great Nations of Anti=<lb/>
=quity, &amp; their Agriculture consequently was<lb/>
unconnected with any speculative chemical<lb/>
principles" - It was an Art brought by continued<lb/>
labour to a certain degree of perfection; but the<lb/>
knowledge was purely empirical &amp; independent<lb/>
of any general system of philosophy. -<lb/>
- The most important part perhaps of<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">chemistry</hi> of Vegetation "that relating to<lb/>
the food of plants" was very early a subject<lb/>
of attention; but accurate knowledge upon<lb/>
it has only been obtained within the last<lb/>
thirty years -<lb/>
The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Greek philosophers</hi> had formed<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
opinions on the matter, but they were the<lb/>
vague generalizations of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">talents</hi>, unassisted<lb/>
by experiment or observation - Water, Air<lb/>
Earth &amp; Fire were necessarily supposed to<lb/>
be the principles of all things - but Water<lb/>
was the favourite Element<lb/>
"- The expression of<lb/>
the Poet; was a grand philosophical<lb/>
Dogma transmitted by the Greeks to the Romans<lb/>
&amp; adopted even by the earlier Chemists -<lb/>
- There is a famous exp<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">t</hi>. on this idea made<lb/>
by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag13"
                ref="#person_221"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag13" type="person">
          Van Helmont
        </name>
            </rs>". which He considered as<lb/>
proving not only that <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">plants</hi> were formed<lb/>
from Water but likewise that Earth might<lb/>
be composed from it. - <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag14"
                ref="#person_221"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag14" type="person">
          Van Helmont
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
watered a willow for five years with<lb/>
distilled water - And He found at<lb/>
the end of that time that it had gained<lb/>
119 pounds whilst the Earth in which it<lb/>
grew had only suffered a loss of three ounces. -<lb/>
This exp<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">t</hi>. was published about the year 1610<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
9<lb/>
&amp; was repeated by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag15"
                ref="#person_103"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag15" type="person">
          the celebrated Boyle
        </name>
            </rs> who<lb/>
seemed inclined to the conclusion "<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">That</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">both Vegetable matter &amp; Earth might be com=</hi>
            <lb/>
=<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">posed</hi> in the processes of Nature, from mere<lb/>
moisture. -<lb/>
- It was not till 1699 that the fact<lb/>
was seen in the true point of view, &amp; that<lb/>
in consequence of the researches of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag16"
                ref="#person_039"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag16" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Woodward</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
who published <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag17"
                ref="#otherwork_260"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag17">
            a paper in the 21 V<hi rend="superscript">o</hi> of "Phil:<lb/>Trans."
        </bibl>
            </rs> in which He shewed that Water in<lb/>
all its common states contained Earth "&amp; other<lb/>
foreign ingredients - &amp; He proved "That<lb/>
the increase of weight of plants nourished by<lb/>
water was in some measure proportional to<lb/>
the materials dissolved in the water." That<lb/>
they grew fastest in impure water &amp; in river<lb/>
water, less in rain water, &amp; least of all in<lb/>
distilled water -" &amp; He concluded "That though<lb/>
moisture was an essential part of the food of<lb/>
plants yet that it was not their only food"<lb/>
&amp; He shewed "that <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">there was no</hi> reason for<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">supposing it convertible into Earth</hi>" - &amp; that<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
the substances contained in soils are essential to healthy<lb/>
vegetation. -<lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag18"
