they all contained different proportions of<lb/>
the four Earths" &amp; that no given mixture<lb/>
was uniformly connected either with fertility<lb/>
or barreness" -<lb/>
- He examined the ashes of the various<lb/>
species of grain &amp; He found in different<lb/>
cases different mixtures of the primitive<lb/>
Earths; from which He concluded "that<lb/>
no given portion was absolutely essential<lb/>
to their health. - a fact of considerable<lb/>
importance &amp; which has been since con=<lb/>
=firmed by the researches of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag156"
                ref="#person_048"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag156" type="person">
          T-de Saussure
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="34"
                xml:id="pb-34"
                facs="#i34"/>
            <lb/>
who found "That plants growing upon<lb/>
a Siliceous soil gave principally on anal=<lb/>
=ysis' Siliceous Earth &amp; those growing upon<lb/>
calcareous soils - <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">calcareous Earth</hi>"<lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag157"
                ref="#otherwork_92"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag157">
            Bergman's Essay
        </bibl>
            </rs> still retains its<lb/>
