            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="57"
                xml:id="pb-57"
                facs="#i57"/>
            <lb/>
55<lb/>
- The barks of trees &amp; of plants principally<lb/>
consist of woody fibre being in many vege=<lb/>
=tables very flexible is used for different<lb/>
purposes of Manufacture - thus hemp consists<lb/>
of cortical filaments. -<lb/>
- In large trees the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">barks</hi> are the parts<lb/>
that contain astringent matter - The<lb/>
oak is the tree which in our climate affords<lb/>
the largest quantity of astringent principles<lb/>
5 pounds of Oak bark being sufficient to<lb/>
form a pound of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Leather</hi> 7 pounds of the<lb/>
bark of the Spanish chesnut are equal<lb/>
to 5 pounds of Oak bark &amp; the barks of<lb/>
the Elm &amp; the Elder are about half<lb/>
so valuable. -<lb/>
- Many of the trees in our Colonies<lb/>
are more rich in the Tanning or astringent<lb/>
principles than the oak bark. -<lb/>
- The fluids contained in the cells<lb/>
or pores of the organs of plants or which<lb/>
circulate through their vessels have been<lb/>
as yet very little examined as to their<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="58"
                xml:id="pb-58"
                facs="#i58"/>
            <lb/>
Chemical Composition -<lb/>
- The sap in those plants <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which</del> upon <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">which</add>
            <lb/>
accurate exp<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
