            <lb/>
On Mountains &amp; in plains the Natural Soil is<lb/>
usually of the same Chemical Nature as the stratum<lb/>
on which it rests; but in vallies, where torrents<lb/>
have acted, or where the sea has retired from the Land.<lb/>
there is usually a mixture of materials &amp; the surface<lb/>
contains ingredients derived from various sources; -<lb/>
&amp; in some cases whole strata when not of great<lb/>
thickness have been converted into finely divided<lb/>
Earth -<lb/>
- The number of the species of Rocks which<lb/>
existing in great masses from the known interior<lb/>
strata of the globe is not very considerable &amp;<lb/>
they are associated together in different Countries -<lb/>
in similar arrangements. -<lb/>
- The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">soils</hi> into which their upper surfaces<lb/>
have decomposed are easily distinguished from<lb/>
each other &amp; they form what may be called the<lb/>
primitive Species -<lb/>
