                rend="underline">Country</hi>. -<lb/>
- A due proportion between the earthy<lb/>
&amp; the organisable parts of the soil is essential<lb/>
to fertility; - but as the earthy ingredients differ<lb/>
in their Nature so likewise the vegetable matter<lb/>
differ; - Dry &amp; hard fibres of plants may<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="89"
                xml:id="pb-89"
                facs="#i89"/>
            <lb/>
87<lb/>
injure a soil even if in the smallest quantities<lb/>
&amp; render it necessary to pare &amp; burn - whilst<lb/>
a fine light black vegetable mould mixed in<lb/>
certain quantities; must uniformly improve<lb/>
the texture &amp; increase its nutritive powers. -<lb/>
- The Nature of the Earths in the soil &amp;<lb/>
their absorbent powers; &amp; their proportions<lb/>
must materially affect the agency of the vegetable<lb/>
matter -<lb/>
- Thus a dry fine sand would bear much<lb/>
more vegetable earth than a stiff clay or<lb/>
a <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag391"
