            </rs> to them. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="95"
                xml:id="pb-95"
                facs="#i95"/>
            <lb/>
93<lb/>
Lecture 4.<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Manures</hi>
            <lb/>
- In this lecture I shall endeavour to explain<lb/>
the principles of the nature &amp; agency of Manures -<lb/>
&amp; the best methods of applying them - I shall<lb/>
principally confine myself to chemical considerations.-<lb/>
- Plants are capable of growing by the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mere</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">agency</hi> of Water &amp; of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Air</hi>; But as I mentioned<lb/>
in the first lecture the exp.<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">ts</hi> of D<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">r</hi>. <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag434"
                ref="#person_039"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag434" type="person">
          Woodward
        </name>
            </rs> fully<lb/>
prove "that in cases when the water is pure<lb/>
i.e. holds no foreign matters in solution vegetation<lb/>
is exceedingly feeble " -<lb/>
- This fact has been shewn more recently by<lb/>
the researches of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag435"
                ref="#person_040"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag435" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hassenfratz
        </name>
            </rs> - <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag436"
                ref="#otherwork_021"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag436">
            His paper may<lb/>be found in the "<hi rend="underline">Annales de Chimie</hi>"
        </bibl>
            </rs> He<lb/>
made diff<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">t</hi>. seeds grow &amp; - &amp; He found that<lb/>
when the water was pure - they were always sickly<lb/>
&amp; puny &amp; never produced perfect seeds<lb/>
My Exp<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">t</hi>
            <lb/>
- Turnip seeds in in a soil containing only<lb/>
the pure Earths watered with distilled water -<lb/>
The other the same earths with 4 tea teaspoonfulls<lb/>
of nearly as <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">3</hi> to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">4</hi>. -<lb/>
- A certain proportion of Nutritive matter<lb/>
must be supplied to plants from the soil<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="96"
                xml:id="pb-96"
                facs="#i96"/>
            <lb/>
in which they grow - On the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">method</hi> of<lb/>
supplying this the System of Manuring depends<lb/>
a subject which all others in this department<lb/>
is most capable of being illustrated by the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Principles</hi> of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Chemistry</hi>. -<lb/>
- Possessing no organs of Digestion - plants<lb/>
are nourished from the Roots only by means of<lb/>
small capillary vessels not perceptible to the<lb/>
naked eye &amp; capable of admitting fluid matter<lb/>
only. -<lb/>
- No <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">other substances</hi> consequently can be<lb/>
active as <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">manures</hi> except such as are in the<lb/>
liquid form or such as supply principles<lb/>
soluble in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">water</hi>. -<lb/>
- Though the forms &amp; appearances of<lb/>
vegetables are so wonderfully diversified,<lb/>
yet the elementary principles of which they are<lb/>
composed are exceedingly analogous &amp; but<lb/>
few in number. -<lb/>
- When any <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">parts of a plant</hi> or when <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">all</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">its parts</hi> are decomposed by Heat in close<lb/>
vessels - They evolve more than 2/3 of their<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="97"
                xml:id="pb-97"
                facs="#i97"/>
            <lb/>
95<lb/>
weight in elastic matter which is water,<lb/>
fixed air or <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag437"
                ref="#chemical_058"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag437">
                  <hi rend="underline">Carbonic</hi> acid 
          
        </term>
            </rs>&amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag438"
                ref="#chemical_072"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag438">
                  <hi rend="underline">Hydrocarbonate</hi>
               </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
And what remains in the vessel is <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag439"
                ref="#chemical_140"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag439">
                  <hi rend="underline">charcoal</hi>
               </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
mixed with minute quantities of earths &amp; salts. -<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Instance</hi>
            <lb/>
- This is a simple but at the same time a<lb/>
beautiful experiment - for it will be found to<lb/>
elucidate in the highest degree the nature of<lb/>
the food of plants &amp; the operation of manures<lb/>
upon them. -<lb/>
- The great constituent parts are the same<lb/>
in all cases; but certain plants particularly<lb/>
those which are the common food of Animals -<lb/>
produce - <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag440"
                ref="#chemical_017"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag440">
          Nitrogene
          
        </term>
            </rs>, &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag441"
                ref="#chemical_003"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag441">
          Ammonia
          
        </term>
            </rs> amongst their<lb/>
volatile products &amp; their ashes contain<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag442"
                ref="#chemical_051"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag442">
          phosphate of Lime
          
        </term>
            </rs>. -<lb/>
Barley - Wheat <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Turnips Radishes</hi>
            <lb/>
cabbages &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">grasses</hi>. -<lb/>
- Of the principles of plants a considerable<lb/>
portion is derived from the Atmosphere by their<lb/>
leaves - &amp; the remainder from the Soil. -<lb/>
The substances taken up from the Soil<lb/>
- The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Substances</hi> active as manures may be<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="98"
                xml:id="pb-98"
                facs="#i98"/>
            <lb/>
divided into three general kinds -<lb/>
1. Manures from the decomposition of<lb/>
vegetable matter. -<lb/>
2. Animal, -<lb/>
3. <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag443"
                ref="#chemical_167"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag443">
          saline
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; Earthy compounds. -<lb/>
- <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Vegetable substances</hi> in their decomposing<lb/>
state contain the same elements as in<lb/>
their living state; it is consequently very<lb/>
easy to conceive them convertible into the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">food</hi> of growing plants; - The same in<lb/>
essence there can be no question, but<lb/>
concerning the form in which they are most<lb/>
capable of nourishing &amp; the best mode of<lb/>
their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">application</hi> . -<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Liquidity</hi> or solubility in Water as I have<lb/>
said before is absolutely necessary: - And<lb/>
no matter wholly incapable of decomposition<lb/>
or solution can ever be the nourishment of<lb/>
plants. -<lb/>
- There are a number of substances in the<lb/>
different parts of plants soluble in water,<lb/>
but very few of them appear fitted for<lb/>
the healthy food of crops in their pure or<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="99"
                xml:id="pb-99"
                facs="#i99"/>
            <lb/>
97<lb/>
unaltered states - <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag444"
                ref="#misc_192"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag444">
          Mucilage
        </term>
            </rs>, Sugar &amp; Gelly<lb/>
may be procured in solution from almost all<lb/>
plants; &amp; Extractive matters. Tanning prin=<lb/>
=ciple. &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag445"
                ref="#chemical_079"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag445">
          gallic acid
          
        </term>
            </rs> from the parts of trees<lb/>
but these substances till they have been submitted<lb/>
for some time to the action of Air so as to have<lb/>
undergone a change in their nature seem to<lb/>
have no beneficial effect - I made an exp.<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">t</hi>
            <lb/>
last year on the effect of these substances in their<lb/>
pure states &amp; I shall mention the facts &amp;<lb/>
the general results - I watered from the<lb/>
14 - to 26 of May some plants of Mint &amp; some<lb/>
common meadow grass planted in diff<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">t</hi>. pots,<lb/>
in garden earths respectively with weak solutions<lb/>
of the diff<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">t</hi>. substances that have been named -<lb/>
&amp; one pot of grass was watered with a solution<lb/>
of all of them:<lb/>
Tanning principle Extractive matter<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag446"
                ref="#misc_192"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag446">
          Mucilage
        </term>
            </rs>, Gelly Sugar Tanning princi<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ple</add>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag447"
                ref="#chemical_079"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag447">
          gallic acid
          
        </term>
            </rs> extractive matter.<lb/>
The effect was certainly pernicious -<lb/>
parts of the solutions not consumed in these<lb/>
exp<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">ts</hi>. were suffered to remain exposed to Air<lb/>
till Sept<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">r</hi>. 5<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">th</hi> when they had all fermented<lb/>
changed in colour &amp; acquired a strong musty<lb/>
smell - I employed them in this state a<lb/>
fortnight upon pots of Earth filled in this same<lb/>
way - &amp; they all increased the growth of the<lb/>
grass except the solutions of extractive matter<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="100"
                xml:id="pb-100"
                facs="#i100"/>
            <lb/>
&amp; of sugar &amp; on examining these I found<lb/>
sour Vinegar had formed in them. -<lb/>
- These exp<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">ts</hi>,, convinced me that plants: will<lb/>
not take up or cannot be nourished by specific<lb/>
fluids of the same kind as those found in<lb/>
their living vessels; &amp; that fermentation performs<lb/>
for them what digestion effects for animals -<lb/>
provides a food in which the elements are loosely<lb/>
combined &amp; capable of being easily assimilated<lb/>
to the living organs. -<lb/>
- The substances in plants soluble in<lb/>
water are much more susceptible of fermen=<lb/>
=tation than those which are insoluble. -<lb/>
The compounds that I have just mentioned all<lb/>
decompose in their aqueous solutions when<lb/>
exposed to air in the course of a few weeks; -<lb/>
but the resinous &amp; oily parts of plants remain<lb/>
unalterable for a great length of Time - &amp;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Woody fibre</hi> or the fibrous part of plants<lb/>
when deprived of soluble matter continues<lb/>
for years very little changed. -<lb/>
- Pure oil &amp; resinous matters seem very<lb/>
little capable in their unmixed state of<lb/>
increasing vegetation. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="101"
                xml:id="pb-101"
                facs="#i101"/>
            <lb/>
99<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag448"
                ref="#place_017"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag448" type="place">
                  <hi rend="underline">Roehampton</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">March Cresses - Turnips</hi>
            <lb/>
            <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">injured</unclear>
            <lb/>
- Pure Woody fibre from the best reports seems like=<lb/>
=wise of little use<lb/>
- Tanners spent bark the Tan has generally been<lb/>
found of very little efficacy -<lb/>
- The soluble parts of plants can in very<lb/>
few cases be employed unmixed as manure<lb/>
the only instance that I am acquainted with is<lb/>
that of the Water of flax &amp; hemp which contains<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag449"
                ref="#misc_192"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag449">
          Mucilage
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; extractive matter &amp; which rapidly<lb/>
runs into fermentation -<lb/>
- This <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag450"
                ref="#person_041"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag450" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Billingsley
        </name>
            </rs> mentions as an <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">excellent</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">manure</hi> -<lb/>
- I have heard a good account of the use of<lb/>
water in which flax has been steeped in the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag451"
                ref="#place_437"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag451" type="place">
          North of Ireland
        </name>
            </rs>. -<lb/>
- When the entire parts of plants are submitted<lb/>
in the moist state to the agency of Air at a<lb/>
temperature between 50 &amp; 90 - By the reaction<lb/>
between the fluid &amp; solid parts &amp; the attraction<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag452"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag452">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs> a speedy change is produced -<lb/>
much <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag453"
                ref="#chemical_058"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag453">
          Carbonic Acid
          
        </term>
            </rs> is evolved, &amp; a peculiar<lb/>
fetid fluid is formed Heat is produced - Water<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="102"
                xml:id="pb-102"
                facs="#i102"/>
            <lb/>
; produced; - &amp; if the process be suffered to<lb/>
go on. till naturally exhausted nothing<lb/>
remains but <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag454"
                ref="#chemical_167"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag454">
          saline
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; earthy matter with<lb/>
a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">little <rs xml:id="ttag455" ref="#chemical_140" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag455">
          charcoal
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi> - &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the same results</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">are obtained slowly</hi>, &amp; by the operation<lb/>
of the external elements, as would be<lb/>
rapidly produced by combustion, &amp; artificial<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Heat</hi>. -<lb/>
- It is not at all necessary for fer=<lb/>
=mentation - That the Vegetable matter<lb/>
should be in great heaps or masses - The<lb/>
smallest leaf when exposed under proper cir=<lb/>
=cumstances undergoes the change - &amp; when<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">green grasses</hi> are ploughed in; the process<lb/>
takes place as effectually beneath the soil<lb/>
as if the whole had been <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mowed</hi> &amp; collected<lb/>
in a great dunghill - the Heat undoubtedly<lb/>
is less - the process is less vivid but as<lb/>
much soluble matter is formed &amp;<lb/>
&amp; less nutritive [space for insertion] is dissipated &amp; lost. -<lb/>
- Whenever Vegetable Matter is moist &amp;<lb/>
juicy; - Theory would evidently direct its<lb/>
immediate use. - &amp; that it should be<lb/>
ploughed into the Soil as soon as possible -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="103"
                xml:id="pb-103"
                facs="#i103"/>
            <lb/>
101<lb/>
Pond weeds, the parings of Hedges &amp; ditches, &amp;<lb/>
sea-weed all ought to be used as soon as possible,<lb/>
&amp; in these points the best practise (I believe)<lb/>
accords with Scientific principle. - |_ On the<lb/>
coast of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag456"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag456" type="place">
          Cornwall
        </name>
            </rs> &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag457"
                ref="#place_162"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag457" type="place">
          Devonshire
        </name>
            </rs> Sea weeds are used<lb/>
in large quantities particularly as a dressing for<lb/>
Barley. - the ancient practice was to collect<lb/>
them in the autumn &amp; winter &amp; make them<lb/>
into a [space for insertion] with sand - &amp; they were suffered<lb/>
to remain many months before they were applied -<lb/>
- Of late years they have ploughed them in fresh.<lb/>
- &amp; I was informed by some of the most Intelli=<lb/>
=gent Farmers on the Coast the year before last<lb/>
that they found the effect of fresh weeds<lb/>
much greater than an equal quantity of the<lb/>
fermented weeds -<lb/>
- Dry, hard &amp; compact Vegetable substances<lb/>
which contains little soluble matter or which<lb/>
have been deprived of it by the agency of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Water</hi>
            <lb/>
absolutely require preparation to be rendered<lb/>
efficient manures &amp; it is necessary that some<lb/>
substances should be mixed with them to begin<lb/>
the work of fermentation - Of this kind<lb/>
are <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">peat spent Bark chips of wood, Sawdust</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="104"
                xml:id="pb-104"
                facs="#i104"/>
            <lb/>
Such substances if ploughed into the land in<lb/>
their common state would remain for years<lb/>
&amp; would very slowly decompose. |_&amp; though<lb/>
they might by their mechanical operation<lb/>
in some case as in those of stiff clays or<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag458"
                ref="#chemical_112"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag458">
          marles
          
        </term>
            </rs> improve the texture of the soil yet<lb/>
in other cases such as those of sands &amp;<lb/>
gravel soils they would injure it. -<lb/>
- Inert Vegetable matters are in all cases<lb/>
brought into a state of quick decomposition<lb/>
by being mixed with fresh vegetable substances<lb/>
or with the dung of animals, &amp;<lb/>
such mixtures there is every reason to believe<lb/>
would be efficacious if applied to land as<lb/>
soon as made - In <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag459"
                ref="#otherwork_071"
                type="otherwork">
