139<lb/>
Lecture 6.<lb/>
Nourishment &amp; growth of Plants.<lb/>
The next objects of enquiry are the processes<lb/>
of the nourishment &amp; growth of plants -<lb/>
These are objects which have been very much<lb/>
elucidated by late researches of physiologists<lb/>
&amp; Chemists; they offer many beautiful philo=<lb/>
=sophical truths &amp; afford some applications<lb/>
which may be of practical utility to Agriculture<lb/>
- In the sprouting or germination of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">seeds</hi>
            <lb/>
the presence of a certain degree of Heat, of water<lb/>
&amp; of Air is necessary - &amp; without the concurrence<lb/>
of these agents they are wholly incapable of<lb/>
growing. -<lb/>
- The seed consists of three <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">parts</hi>. the<lb/>
great mass of it is formed by the organ of<lb/>
nourishment which consists either of one <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag748" ref="#chemical_213" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag748">
          cotyledon
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <lb/>
or two cotyledons of a radicle or plumala<lb/>
Instance<lb/>
- When a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">seed</hi> is placed in contact with moisture<lb/>
at a temperature above 40 degrees. the epidermis or<lb/>
coat by which it is surrounded gradually becomes<lb/>
looser. - Its Cotyledons are enlarged in their<lb/>
dimensions &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag749"
                ref="#chemical_078"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag749">
          elastic fluid
          
        </term>
            </rs> is given out from<lb/>
