                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag860" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> K
        </name>
            </rs> -<lb/>
tapped several trees in diff.<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">t</hi> places<lb/>
at the time the sap was beginning<lb/>
to rise &amp; He found that in proportion<lb/>
as the sap was taken from a high part<lb/>
of the trunk or branches, so in proportion<lb/>
it was found of greater specific gravity<lb/>
&amp; more loaded with saccharine matter. -<lb/>
- M<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">r</hi>. K - has made a general appli=<lb/>
=cation of his principles - |_In <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">plants,</hi>
            <lb/>
that have <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">bulbous</hi> roots the nourish=<lb/>
=ment derived from the Autumnal<lb/>
sap is laid up in the fleshy part<lb/>
of the root; &amp; hence they are prepared<lb/>
to shoot forth the moment the warmth<lb/>
of spring begins its actions upon their<lb/>
of spring begins its action upon their<lb/>
living parts. -<lb/>
- In annual plants there is no system<lb/>
of organs for the reception of the nutritive<lb/>
matter of the sap &amp; the whole of the<lb/>
contents of the sap vessels appear to be<lb/>
exhausted in the formation of the seed"<lb/>
- It is evident on these facts that<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="170"
                xml:id="pb-170"
                facs="#i170"/>
            <lb/>
perennial Grapes ought never to be cropt<lb/>
very close in the end of Autumn - for<lb/>
in this case the saccharine matter which<lb/>
would have been their first nourishment<lb/>
in the spring will be destroyed; &amp; they<lb/>
will rise feebly &amp; with difficulty: -<lb/>
- It is on the same principle that<lb/>
the tuberous part of the potato ought<lb/>
never to be cut off round the bud or<lb/>
eye - for it is in this case deprived of<lb/>
the greatest part of that matter which<lb/>
would have afforded to it an essential<lb/>
nourishment &amp; at the time when it is<lb/>
most needed &amp; when the powers of the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">roots are</hi> most feeble. -<lb/>
- I have already mentioned that many<lb/>
of the substances found in vegetables are<lb/>
convertible into such other &amp; that they<lb/>
differ principally not as to the nature<lb/>
of their elements but as to the properties<lb/>
of them. - So that Sugar Tan<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">g</hi>. principle<lb/>
resin <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag861"
                ref="#misc_192"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag861">
          Mucilage
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; woody fibre are all<lb/>
            <lb/>
